variant of   Wayland  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wieland","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Otto, Heinz, Dieter, Dietrich, Erdmann, Florian, Franz, Fritz, Gerhard.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wīg</i> ‘war’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This name was borne by the supernaturally skilled smith of ancient Germanic folk legend, and for this reason it may in part have been given as a nickname to blacksmiths.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): presumably an adoption of the German surname."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Weyland I was born in 1180, in Westerfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas de Weyland I, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. Marsila De Wyland of Baylham, was 20. He married Beatrix de Suffolk. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1225, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1180–1225":"1180–1225","1185–1200":"1185–1200","1184–Female":"1184–Surnud","1205–1259":"1205–1259","1150–1210":"1150–1210","1160–1180":"1160–1180","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Westerfield, Suffolk, England":"Westerfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1180–1225":"1180–1225","1185–1200":"1185–1200","1184–Female":"1184–Kuollut","1205–1259":"1205–1259","1150–1210":"1150–1210","1160–1180":"1160–1180","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Westerfield, Suffolk, England":"Westerfield, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1180–1225":"1180–1225","1185–1200":"1185–1200","1184–Female":"1184–Décédée","1205–1259":"1205–1259","1150–1210":"1150–1210","1160–1180":"1160–1180","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1185":"1185","1184":"1184","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Westerfield, Suffolk, England":"Westerfield, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, Angleterre","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre